review: This book was a gift from my queen of impeccable taste Liz Norton so I KNEW it was going to be good! Going to try and give a  without giving awaThis book was a gift from my queen of impeccable taste Liz Norton so I KNEW it was going to be good! Going to try and give a  without giving away spoilers so here we go:I LOVE a multi-character interwoven tale - especially one over the course of thousands of years. I thought the continuity was very clever and seamless, and I loved the owl symbolism throughout. I really felt attached to Zeno particularly, he was such a sweetly written narrator. His last chapter made me tear up.My warning for this book is that readers have to be patient. It’s a little slow at the beginning and REALLY picks up the pace in the second half. I personally couldn’t put it down for the last two sittings. Don’t let the page count be daunting, there’s a lot of blank pages switching between narrations.My biggest gripe is that I wasn’t so interested in Anna’s or Omeir’s stories and was always a bit disinterested when I had to go back to their POVs. I understood the importance of them but … eh. My second biggest gripe is that we didn’t get enough of Konstance’s story. Her’s was certainly the most exciting and action packed tale, and yet they wrapped her story up WAY too quickly and IMO left the world building severely underdeveloped. Without getting into the weeds of it, I still have so many unanswered questions! Her time jump really threw me off and I was really bummed we didn’t get more context, I could’ve read a book of just her journey alone so I was really bummed that hers felt the most rushed....more

review: My last book of this year ended up being my most difficult to read as well as to rate.I’ve never struggled THIS hard through a book and only began to My last book of this year ended up being my most difficult to read as well as to rate.I’ve never struggled THIS hard through a book and only began to get the hang of it with less than half the book remaining. It was so complicated and had incredibly dense world building to a point that I ended up using a chapter by chapter synopsis Reddit post to help me move along. The politics, the religions, the sciences, the lore, the social etiquette, the names of places/people, it was a LOT for the first entire HALF of the book, where I felt like nothing was happening along side of world building.I’ve NEVER been so frustrated reading a book. If it wasn’t a a book club pick, I don’t know if I would’ve been able to persevere. I hate to say it was too smart for me, but it was a bit too smart for me.That being said, the second half was a beautiful story: way more enjoyable and easy to digest. Overall, my low  relies heavily on the fact that I didn’t understand a lot of the concepts at the speed they were introduced and couldn’t stay focused. The discussions around gender were fascinating and truly revolutionary for the time it was written, for that reason alone I’m still so glad I read it.I’m confident that if I am ever to reread this book in the future, I would enjoy it much more. That’s no fault of the author or the book itself, more so a personal objective of my own....more

title: Giovanni's Room
author: Baldwin, James
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: 4.5 stars - It took me awhile to figure out my feelings about this rating. To start, this is such a beautifully written book, every detail feels metic4.5 stars - It took me awhile to figure out my feelings about this rating. To start, this is such a beautifully written book, every detail feels meticulously planned to create each city scape and social circle of Paris. I really did feel transported to every smoky bar, every uneven street, and of course - to Giovanni’s room.The love story centering this book is such a delight to read (at first). The scene of them eating oysters and drinking white wine at 6 in the morning will always stick with me. It feels very much like a coming of age story, which always have a soft spot in my heart.Now comes the worst part of this book and the reason I couldn’t give this book a 5 star: our narrator, David. David becomes not only the worst character of the book, but to me, one of the most despicable characters that I’ve read. I found myself rooting for every person that lashed out on David for his selfish and manipulative actions. His ‘woe is me’ attitude was the worst, he just got worse and worse as the book went on and I was frustrated to have to “stick with” his perspective throughout the story. This got me thinking; do I *~have~* to like a narrator in order to truly rate a book? Isn’t my hatred of him exemplifying how talented James Baldwin is as a writer? This book is so wonderfully written otherwise, do I really need to identify with the narrator in order to enjoy it? I don’t know the answer right now, but it gave me something to think about moving forward with my ratings.Overall, this is an incredible story if you’re looking for something fast to break your heart. I watched the James Baldwin documentary ‘I Am Not Your Negro’, based off the completed pages of his last, unfinished novel before he died, before finishing the book and it gave me some great insight to James as a whole. I’m definitely going to look more into his work and his life after this....more

review: I wanted to like it. I really did. But I just couldn’t. The plot is repetitive and boring. I felt like I forgot what had just happened in it every timI wanted to like it. I really did. But I just couldn’t. The plot is repetitive and boring. I felt like I forgot what had just happened in it every time I picked it back up. My biggest gripe is that Holden is probably the least likable ‘protagonist’ I’ve ever read. He’s pompous, obnoxious, and above all, ANNOYING. His catchphrases, his train of thought, his “deep” philosophy, all of it. “BuT tHaT’s tHe PoInt mAdIsOn! HeS yOuNg aNd DuMb!!!” I don’t CARE!!! I was so frustrated with him by the end of the book.I totally get why this is every moody 16 year old boy’s favorite. Holden is the epitome of a selfish, fake intellectual asshat who thinks he knows better than everyone: the only “real” one out there. Never mind the fact that he’s grieving (which is one of the only redeeming qualities of the book being the depiction of a teen dealing with a traumatic loss), I just never found myself rooting for him. Sure, I felt sorry for him, but that’s about it.Overall this was a huuuuuge let down. Honestly, I wish I read it in highschool so that I could dig through some themes and discuss it with others—maybe I would’ve liked it more and maybe I would’ve resonated with Holden. But reading it alone with a fully developed frontal cortex was not ideal....more

Barbara moves seamlessly between each of our narrators, and her attention to detail is incredible—down to the innocent misspellings of a 5 year old, the eerie palindromes of a stoic and crippled genius, and the incorrect use of words from a vain, dumb teenager. This book is overflowing with beautiful, haunting metaphors and imagery. I was captivated the whole time and invested in each out our narrators’ journeys. She never left me hanging when it came to wrapping up every character’s arc, which I really appreciated. review: Starting off by saying that I loooooooove this topic AND the author’s podcast about this topic, so my  is very biased and I acknowledge that.I fStarting off by saying that I loooooooove this topic AND the author’s podcast about this topic, so my  is very biased and I acknowledge that.I found this book really easy to read in Amanda’s voice and cadence, but can understand the point that some found her style a little scattered and repetitive (lots of “but more on that later” when introducing topics). Overall, this was SO fun to read and well researched. I was a little worried there would be too much overlap between this and her pod, but that wasn’t the case at all. To be honest, I often find myself wishing she would delve deeper into the historical “classic cults” more on her podcast, and this book definitely scratched that itch. However, that makes this book a tad more morbid than SLAC, so if true crime cults aren’t your jam, this might not be the one for you.I recommend this for all my true crime girlies, but especially (and obviously) my ‘Sounds Like a Cult’ girlies. Amanda is such a fun nonfiction pick and I’m excited to read her others!!...more

I’ve heard wonderful things about Joan’s writing style, and these essays certainly upheld that notion, but I often found myself bored of the topics. I was so excited when she started off with essays involving The Doors and the Manson Family, but that quickly disintegrated into essays about key 60’s figureheads I didn’t know, historical events I wasn’t familiar with, and an essay about the mechanics of a water reclamation plant. I’m chalking up my less-than-stellar  due to my own [lack of] knowledge of the topics discussed, not against Joan and her writing. This was my first Didion and perhaps shouldn’t have been, but I have two more books of hers on hand to try out and will not let this deter me! review: Maybe it’s the fact that I read this book during the one week span of my dad’s death anniversary date and Mother’s Day, but this book meant so much toMaybe it’s the fact that I read this book during the one week span of my dad’s death anniversary date and Mother’s Day, but this book meant so much to me and I’m so glad I read it. ‘Cool’ is not the right word, but it was… such a relief to see the aspects of profound parental loss (that I’ve always been too scared to share with my peers) written into such a beautiful book. Especially as an only child as well, I’ve never related to a book to this same degree before. I felt connected with Michelle, and everyone else who has gone through the ringer of losing a parent in your early twenties. This kind of loss such an isolating experience, and yet it still unites us at the core to have look into the face of death and hold the burden of knowing the ugliest truth about the world. Michelle does a wonderful job of conveying the trials and tribulations of navigating taking on a new role in her family as a caretaker (and eventually) an executor while balancing it with newfound trauma and grief.This book is so raw and devastating but it’s real. It’ll always hold a really special place in my art as the book that showed me just how beautiful the art made from this type of pain can be. The love she has for her mother is so palpable and it’s shown me the importance and power of creating art as a guide to memorialize a loved one. To be honest, if I hadn’t have gone through this type of loss before I don’t think I would’ve rated this book nearly as high as I did. It was beautifully written, but the emotional connection and time to reflect on my own grief is what really made this such an important book for me....more

The tangents about characters that we hear from ONCE, and countless descriptions of short, made up sci fi books that aren’t relevant to the plot at all, take up a lot of page real estate, and make staying focused a little difficult. I don’t think this is his best, or his funniest, work by any means. I think there’s a lot of bullshit, a lot of pointless drawings, and not a whole lot of story progression. That being said, I still found myself flying through it, because I did love the storyline itself, but I just didn’t get *~enough~* of it. title: The Goldfinch
author: Tartt, Donna
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Not even sure where to begin with this one. Crushed the first 200 pages in one day, slowed to about 30-40 a day and then had to fully stop for about aNot even sure where to begin with this one. Crushed the first 200 pages in one day, slowed to about 30-40 a day and then had to fully stop for about a month. This book is gorgeous and captivating but it is also a cesspool of anxiety and despair. It broke my heart soooo many times. Donna weaves such an incredible story, it’s almost too real sometimes. I’ve never been so anxious over a book before. This, of course, got me thinking: isn’t this what a good book is supposed to do? Immerse readers in a world and make them really feel with the character? To understand and care for fictional beings?? But honestly, it was too much sometimes, especially with how tragic it is from start to finish.This book was an absolute behemoth. It covers SO much ground, sometimes too slowly, but it was never a bore to read. Looking back, there’s a lot of fluff in its nearly 800 pages, but it’s all so beautiful. I would give this a five star  if it weren’t for the anxiety. Despite it being such a phenomenal book, I’m fairly hesitant to openly recommend it. Even now after finishing it, I’m feeling a little unsatisfied. I feel like I have grieved so much while reading, I’m not sure how else to describe it. Was it an incredibly fuckin journey? Absolutely. Was it worth the devastation? I’m not sure....more

review: **spoiler alert** My third Jane Austen is my favorite by far. While I think Jane’s ‘slow burn’ romantic plots are delicious, I find them a little pred**spoiler alert** My third Jane Austen is my favorite by far. While I think Jane’s ‘slow burn’ romantic plots are delicious, I find them a little predictable at this point. For some reason, that still doesn’t deter from my audible gasping at one of her classically dramatic declarations of adoration. I love Jane for that dearly.On top of a slow burn, Jane loves to throw in a wrench of two seemingly unsuited side characters getting quickly married in secret. I couldn’t help but be a tad disappointed at this particular plot line, thinking I had the rest of the book figured out already. However, there was another element of deception (that I haven’t seen in her others) that really elevated the storyline for me and kept me engaged.I’m fortunate to have read my Jane Austen’s in the order I did: Pride and Prejudice first, then Emma, and finally Persuasion. It was so sweet to follow her growth as an author throughout her life, and each ranked in ascending order as I went along. Jane’s writing is a fine wine, and only got better with time. As this was her last completed novel, I truly think it’s her best—and to be a little crass— an incredible high note to go out on.There’s something so satisfying about reaching the climax of one of Jane’s books, which tend to happen 1 or 2 chapters before it ends. Some would find it frustrating to have to wait so long for it, but Jane has a way of making all of it feel *~worth~* it. Like I, as a reader, FINALLY deserved it, and how perfect it was. What a lovely, talented, sarcastic, and sharp woman....more

I wanted to reminisce on the time I did a project on Aphrodite in fourth grade and thus was allowed to read promiscuous Greek myths for hours on end under the guise of ‘research’.In short: I was wrong. This book centers around the escapades of Catherine the Great and took on a common theme of sex, jealousy, and death. Don’t get me wrong, I’m a HUGE fan of secrecy and yearning, but it got repetitive and boring. The most popular and closest thing to sexy this book got was constantly describing Catherine’s boobs as anything ranging from ‘massive’ to ‘spilling out the top of her corset’, you get the gist. It was nothing special nor crazy; we get it, she’s got huge knockers.Was it a quick read? Yes. Does the red hardcover look incredible on my ‘read’ bookshelf? Yes.
